<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-27T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-27T19:00:00-05:00" n="909" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d909">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">300.115(39)/23: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Consul General at Hamburg</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Keblinger</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-27T19:00:00-05:00">October
                                    27, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>121. Referring to your telegram 174, October 25, section 2,<note n="6" xml:id="d909fn6">i. e., the second paragraph of the telegram.</note>
                            American Ambassador London has been instructed to explain circumstances
                            concerning these shipments of wood pulp, their necessity to the paper
                            and related industries in the United States and to express the hope of
                            this Government that these shipments will not be seized or molested.</p>
                        <p>Interested importers have been advised of proposed procedure but find
                            German consular officers without instructions in the matter.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>